# Documentation Conventions

## README Files

READMEs are short and actionable:
1. One-paragraph description
2. Prerequisites
3. Quick deploy (copy-paste commands)
4. Quick test (copy-paste commands)
5. Link to detailed docs

Do NOT put architectural explanations, trade-offs, or decision rationale in READMEs.

## Detailed Documentation

Deep explanations go in:
- `docs/<topic>.md` for cross-module topics
- `modules/<name>/docs/` for module-specific documentation

Include:
- Why decisions were made (not just what)
- Red Hat documentation URLs as references
- Diagrams where they clarify architecture
- Version-specific notes (e.g., "RHOAI 3.3 requires...")

## Architecture Decision Records

Every non-obvious decision gets an ADR in `docs/adr/NNNN-<title>.md`.

ADR template:
```markdown
# ADR-NNNN: <Title>

## Status
Accepted | Superseded by ADR-MMMM

## Context
<What motivated this decision?>

## Options Considered
### Option 1: <Name>
- Pros: ...
- Cons: ...

## Decision
<What we chose and why>

## Consequences
- Positive: ...
- Negative: ...
```

ADRs are critical for:
- RHOAI version upgrades (understanding why current config exists)
- Onboarding (understanding project history)
- Revisiting decisions when constraints change

## Red Hat References

When referencing Red Hat products, always include the official documentation URL:
```markdown
See [RHOAI 3.3 Observability](https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_openshift_ai_self-managed/3.3/html/managing_openshift_ai/managing-observability_managing-rhoai)
```
